Recommendations
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the requisitioning office to prepare and submit the RIS to the Designated GSO for consolidation of all inventories issued by the General Service Office;
Require the Designated GSO to prepare and submit SSMI based on the consolidated RIS submitted by the requisitioning office and to submit the same to the office of the Municipal Accountant to support the recognize inventory expenses;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to recognize the inventory expenses based on the submitted SSMI by the Designated GSO; and
Require the Inventory Committee to submit RPCI to the Office of the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively.

Recommendations
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the account Trust Liabilities – Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund and prepare adjustment entry, if any, to equalize the balance of the account to the reported unexpended balance in the utilization report;
Require MDRRM Officer with the help of the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit a LDRRMFIP, using annex A below, for proper segregation of PPAs between the current year and past years’ unexpended balance of the LDRMMF;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the past years’ unexpended balance of the LDRRMF and segregate per year the unexpended amount to be shown in the Notes to the FS; and
After reconciliation, if an amount is proven to be related from the unexpended balance after five years, instruct the Municipal Accountant to revert back the amount to the General Fund to fund the social services of the agency.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
a) Require the City Engineer to review the unimplemented projects if it is still viable to implement as programmed, if not, consider re-aligning the same for more feasible projects which have a better impact to its constituents after consultation and approval of the City Development Council (CDC);
b) Direct the CDC to ensure that the development projects identified in the Annual Development Plan (ADP) are feasible and can be implemented within the year with the proposed budget allocation;
c) Instruct the City Planning and Development Office to monitor the implementation of programs, projects and activities funded by the 20 percent DF and ascertain if executed in accordance with the approved AIP, in compliance with existing rules and regulations; and
d) Consider augmenting the City’s manpower especially those in-charge in project implementation to improve or increase the number of completed projects during the year and/or consider utilization of other projects through straight contract after undergoing the proper procurement process to expedite the completion of planned projects.

We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to:
a) Determine the projects, programs, or activities to be funded by the PAGCOR fund;
b) Direct the requesting officials or the end users of PAGCOR fund to submit the request for goods, supplies or equipment to the BAC who will undertake the procurement process;
c) Instruct the BAC to strictly implement the use of appropriate methods of procurement provided under the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
d) Discontinue the practice of paying the goods on reimbursement basis, except petty purchases to be paid out of the Petty Cash Fund or through cash advances; and
e) Direct the Acting City Accountant and City Treasurer to ensure that all payments are made by check payable directly to the creditor/ supplier to whom the money is due.

